{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} [[File:Archbishop Patrick Adamson coat of arms.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Henry Adamson's family coat of arms]] '''Henry Adamson''' (1581–1637), was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[poet]] and [[historian]].
Adamson was the son of James Adamson, [[wikt:dean|Dean]] of the [[Merchant]] [[Guild]]ry and [[Provost (civil)|Provost]] of [[Perth, Scotland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfamilyheritage.co.uk/list_perth%20magistrates.shtm|title=Perth Magistrates|publisher=Scottish Family Heritage|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321203119/http://www.scottishfamilyheritage.co.uk/list_perth%20magistrates.shtm|archivedate=21 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> baptised on 11 November 1581.<ref name=ODNB>{{cite web|first=Katharine A.|last=Craik|title=Adamson, Henry (bap. 1581, d. 1637)|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|edition=Online|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/142|accessdate=2015-08-03|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/142}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> Henry set out to train as a [[priest]], after his uncle [[Patrick Adamson]], but instead became a schoolmaster in his home city.<ref>[http://www.electricscotland.com/history/other/adamson_henry.htm Significant Scots: Henry Adamson]</ref> He died before July in the year 1637.<ref name=ODNB/>
His friend [[William Drummond of Hawthornden|William Drummond]] encouraged the publication of his most famous poem: ''Muses Threnodie: of Mirthful Mournings on the death of Mr Gall'', ([[Edinburgh]] 1638 &mdash; see [[1638 in poetry]]). The poem is an important document for its general account of Perth in the seventeenth century. Adamson is credited with first using the word ''[[curling]]'' in 1620. He related that his friend, Mr Gall, "a citizen of Perth, and a gentle-man of goodly stature, and pregnant wit, much given to pastime, as [[golf]], [[Archery|archerie]], curling and jovial companie". It also records the playing of [[History of golf|Golf]] on the [[Perth, Scotland|South Inch]]:
:''And ye, my clubs must no more prepare'' :''To make your balls flee whistling through the air''
It is also particularly noted for its observation of [[rosicrucianism]], [[freemasonry]] and [[second sight]]. Referring to the rebuilding of a bridge over the [[River Tay]], swept away in 1621, Adamson wrote:
:''Thus Mr Gall assured it would be so'' :''And my good genius doth surely know:'' :''For what we do presage is not in grosse'' :''For we be brethren of the Rosie Crosse;'' :''We have the [[Mason word]], and second sight,'' :''Things for to come we can foretell aright.''<ref>''The muses threnodie, or, mirthfull mournings, on the death of Master Gall. Containing varietie of pleasant poëticall descriptions, morall instructions, historiall narrations, and divine observations, with the most remarkable antiquities of Scotland, especially at Perth'' by Henry Adamson, King James College, Edinburgh, 1638</ref>
